meta {
  name: Get Elements
  type: http
  seq: 1
}

post {
  url: {{API_URL}}/databases/{{DB_INSTANCE_ID}}/vectorSet/get-elements
  body: json
  auth: inherit
}

body:json {
  {
    "keyName": "vset:small_3d",
    "start": "-",
    "end": "+",
    "count": 15
  }
}

docs {
  # Get Vector Set Elements

  Returns elements from a Vector Set in **lexicographical order** (alphabetical byte-by-byte comparison).

  ## Request Parameters

  | Parameter | Description |
  |-----------|-------------|
  | `keyName` | The Vector Set key name |
  | `start` | Starting point for the range (use `-` for beginning) |
  | `end` | Ending point for the range (use `+` for end) |
  | `count` | Maximum number of elements to return |

  ## Range Syntax

  | Symbol | Meaning |
  |--------|---------|
  | `-` | Minimum (start from beginning) |
  | `+` | Maximum (end at last element) |
  | `[elem` | Inclusive (include this element) |
  | `(elem` | Exclusive (start after this element) |

  ## Important: Lexicographical Ordering

  Elements are sorted as **strings**, not numbers! This means:

  ```
  item_1 → item_10 → item_11 → item_15 → item_2 → item_3
  ```

  Because `"item_10"` < `"item_2"` when comparing character by character (`'1'` < `'2'`).

  ## Response

  - `total`: Total number of elements in the Vector Set
  - `nextCursor`: Use this as `start` in the next request to paginate (if more elements exist)
  - `elements`: Array of element objects with `name`, `vector`, and `attributes`
}

settings {
  encodeUrl: true
}

